The Path to Nuclear Disarmament
NEW YORK – Weapons of mass destruction and disarmament present one of the most difficult challenges that the world currently faces. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote global public good and find solutions to problems that do not respect borders.
A world without nuclear weapons is a common good of the highest importance.
My interest in this topic is partly based on personal experiences.
My home country, South Korea, has suffered from the devastation of conventional war and has been exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other weapons of mass destruction.
Yet such threat scenarios obviously exist not only in Asia.
Although the use of nuclear weapons has long been considered a taboo, disarmament remains merely an aspiration.
Is a taboo that only refers to the use of such weapons sufficient at all?
When it comes to nuclear weapons, individual states make the most important decisions.
Yet the UN plays a decisive role in this.
We offer a central forum where states can agree on norms that serve their common interests.
We analyze and educate in order to achieve our agreed-upon goals and advocate for them.
Most states have decided to forgo nuclear weapons and summarize their commitments under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
However, some states view such weapons as a status symbol, and some see them as the ultimate deterrent against a nuclear attack, which mainly explains the estimated 26,000 nuclear weapons still in existence.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of nuclear deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and creating new risks that nuclear weapons might be used.
The world is still concerned about nuclear activities in North Korea and Iran, and there is broad support for efforts to address these concerns through peaceful means.
There are also concerns that a "nuclear renaissance" may be ahead of us, as nuclear energy is seen as a clean energy alternative in times of increasing efforts to combat climate change.
The main concern is that this will lead to the production and use of more nuclear material that must be protected against proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are enormous.
Yet the costs and risks of their alternatives never receive the attention they deserve.
Let us think about the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Stockholm International Peace Research Institute), military spending last year rose to over $1.3 trillion.
Ten years ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating the total costs of nuclear weapons in the United States alone at over $5.8 trillion, including future cleanup costs.
That is, by any definition, an enormous investment that could have been used for many other productive purposes.
Concerns about the costs of nuclear weapons and the dangers inherent in them have led to a global idea fire, about how nuclear disarmament could be given new life.
We have experienced the UN Disarmament Commission under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition, and Norway's Seven Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan have established the International Commission for Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament.
Civil society groups and nuclear-armed states have also made proposals, such as the Hoover Plan, introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own Five-Point Plan.
First: I call on all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, in particular the nuclear weapon states, to fulfill their obligations under the treaty and to commence negotiations on effective measures leading to nuclear disarmament.
You could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or they could negotiate a nuclear weapons convention supported by a strong control system, as has long been proposed in the UN.
I have sent a draft of such a convention, which provides a good starting point, to all UN members.
The nuclear powers should actively engage with this issue together with other states at the UN Disarmament Conference in Geneva, the only multilateral disarmament negotiation forum in the world.
The world would also welcome a resumption of bilateral negotiations between the USA and Russia, with the aim of significantly and verifiably reducing their nuclear arsenals.
The governments should also invest more in control research and development.
The UK proposal to hold a conference of nuclear powers on the topic of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: The permanent members of the Security Council should begin discussing security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly convey to the states that do not possess nuclear weapons that they will not be victims of a nuclear weapon use or the threat thereof.
The Council could also convene a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty should stop their nuclear weapons programs and take on their own disarmament commitments.
Thirdly: Unilateral moratoriums on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials may only be allowed up to a certain extent.
We need new efforts to bring the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty into force, as well as initiatives to ensure that the Conference on Disarmament immediately starts negotiations on a treaty on fissile materials without preconditions.
I support the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly endorse efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
Furthermore, I urgently call on all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty to conclude their security agreements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily introduce the stricter security provisions of the Additional Protocol.
Fourthly: The nuclear powers often circulate descriptions of what they do to achieve these goals.
However, these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like to ask the nuclear powers to send such materials to the UN Secretariat and to contribute to their further dissemination.
The fact that there is no significant estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons confirms the need for greater transparency.
And finally, various complementary measures are required.
These include the elimination of other types of weapons of mass destruction, new efforts against terrorism involving weapons of mass destruction, a limitation of the production and trade in conventional weapons and new weapon bans, including for rockets and space weapons.
If there are real, confirmed progress in disarmament, the ability to eliminate the nuclear threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the deadliest weapons in the world and their components, we make it more difficult to carry out terrorist attacks using weapons of mass destruction.
These proposals offer a new beginning, not only for disarmament, but also for strengthening our system of international peace and international security.
